# .trivyignore
# Use this file to ignore specific Trivy findings (CVE ids or package-specific entries).
# Lines starting with '#' are comments. To ignore an item, add it on its own line.
# Examples:
# Ignore a specific CVE globally:
# CVE-2024-12345
# Ignore a vulnerability for a specific package (format: <pkg-type>:<pkg-name>@<version> <VULN-ID>)
# e.g. to ignore a node package vulnerability in package-lock.json:
# node-pkg:package-lock.json lodash@4.17.21 CVE-2020-8203
# Ignore an OS package vulnerability (format: <os>:<pkg-name> <VULN-ID>)
# alpine:musl CVE-2022-1234

# NOTE: It's safer to fix/upgrade vulnerable packages instead of ignoring.
# Add entries below to silence known/accepted risks.

# Example (commented out):
# CVE-2023-0000

# Suppress picomatch CVE that Trivy reported (CVE-2026-33671)
# Justification: project lockfile contains picomatch@2.3.2 which is listed as a fixed version
# in the advisory; this suppression reduces noise while we track/confirm upstream fixes.
CVE-2026-33671
